entry.title: snap-group: Fix re-snap window crash in tablet mode
entry.content:
This cl fixed the crash when snap a secondary snapped window to

primary snapped position. There is no sole culprit for this crash.

Here are some of the main culprits:

1. `OverviewController::CanEnterOverview()` returns false when init

the `SplitViewOverviewSession` as

`IsSplitViewDividerDraggedOrAnimated()` is currently true. This

logic does fix some corner cases but is not always true;

2. The main reason for this crash is that in

`SplitViewController::OnSnapEvent()` uses a hacky way to update

the divider position based on the split view state and windows.

The calculation happens so early that the state and windows are

not updated yet, which leads to the issue that divider animation

starts unexpectedly.

Both of these two are existing issues, which got exposed by a recent

change.



The cl does the following stuff:

1. Remove the divider update logics in

`SplitViewController::OnSnapEvent()`, at which point the states

of `primary_window_` and `secondary_window` are not set yet.

Existing logics are not valid;

2. The divider update logic in `SplitViewController::OnSnapEvent()`

also has a lot of duplications with

`SplitViewController::AttachSnappingWindow()` and

`SplitViewController::OnWindowSnapped()`. This cl did a basic

cleanup of the duplications.

entry.title: Introduce a new flag to reduce TransferSizeUpdated IPC
entry.content:
This CL introduces a new ReduceTransferSizeUpdatedIPC flag.

When this feature is enabled Chromium will send TransferSizeUpdated IPC

from the network service only when DevTools is attached or the request

is for an ad request.

The cost of sending and receiving IPC is not zero. So we hope this can

improve Chromium’s performance and reduce the power consumption.



Note: This feature affects metrics for non-ad resources. We lose the

ability to record incomplete resources in metrics.



# Context

Currently the network service sends the OnTransferSizeUpdated IPC almost

every time it reads the data from the network stack. But the

TransferSizeUpdated IPC is used only for updating DevTools and recording

metrics. Normal users don’t open DevTools while browsing Web pages. And

for normal requests, we don’t need to measure the transferred data size

in real time. The total transferred data can be obtained from

URLLoaderCompletionStatus.encoded_data_length which is passed in

OnComplete() IPC. PageResourceDataUse::DidCompleteResponse() is getting

this value in the renderer process and sending the data to

MetricsWebContentsObserver in the browser process.



But for ad requests, the browser process needs to know the transferred

data size in real time for Heavy ad intervention. So the network service

will continue sending OnTransferSizeUpdated IPC if DevTools is attached

or the request is for an ad even when this feature is enabled.



# History of sending the transfer size

- For legacy IPC, https://crrev.com/80965 started sending the transfer

size in the existing ResourceMsg_DataReceived IPC to show it in

DevTools.

- For mojo-loading without network service, https://crrev.com/439697

started sending the transfer size using a new OnTransferSizeUpdated

IPC only when DevTools is attached.

- For network service, https://crrev.com/545109 started sending the

transfer size using the OnTransferSizeUpdated IPC only when DevTools

is attached. But https://crrev.com/585052 changed it to send the

OnTransferSizeUpdated IPC even when DevTools is not attached to fix

the PageLoadMetricsBrowserTest.ReceivedCompleteResources test failure.

This test is relying on the fact that MetricsWebContentsObserver in

the browser process can observe the transferred data size even when

the request is not finished. This is true when the network service

sends the OnTransferSizeUpdated IPC almost every time it reads the

data from the network stack. But MetricsWebContentsObserver needs to

measure the transferred data size in real time only when the request

is for ad.

entry.title: on-device: adds resilience to on-device
entry.content:
Specifically the following:

. If the gpu is blocked, then don't try connecting and/or starting

another session.

. If there are 3 (controllable via finch) crashes in a row, then

don't reconnect and/or start another session. The count is reset

on success and/or a new version.



This converts the OnDeviceModelServiceController to be ref-counted.

This is done as it makes tracking of crashes much easier (otherwise

each servicecontroller would see the crash).



This also makes it so that if session gets a disconnect the context

is remembered.

entry.title: [Extensions] Add a (failing) test for service worker mismatch
entry.content:
There's a bug where:

* If an extension overrides the NTP and

* An NTP is open and

* An extension update is available and

* The user updates the extension through the chrome://extensions page

to trigger `install_immediately` in the update process,



the resulting extension can run with the old version of the service

worker.



This happens because there's an active controllee of the service worker

at the time we unregister the service worker, which results in an async

unregistration that then conflicts with the new registration.



See more details in

https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1498035#c10 and

https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1498035#c12.



This CL adds a failing test that triggers this behavior. A followup

will fix it.

we will now just wait until the entire table is parsed, by reusing

the new `node_to_parse_before_more_tree_updates_` mechanism.

entry.title: shortcuts: Handle both pre and post rewritten key input events
entry.content:
ShortcutInputHandler now observes both prerewritten events

and rewritten events. Update ShortcutInputProvider observers so that

the shortcut customization app will be able to receive both key

events. Peripheral customization can safely ignore prerewritten events.



Prerewritten input events are "raw" events before any rewriters have

an opportunity to modify the event. Rewrite examples includes remapping

six pack keys (e.g. search + left arrow -> home), remap of

top-row/f-keys (e.g. search + f1 -> browser_back), etc. By sending the

prerewritten event, clients are able to accurately display the

keystrokes pressed/released. This will be used in the shortcut

customization app to inform users what keys are pressed when

editing a shortcut.

entry.title: [User Education] User Ed Experience V2 Session Policy
entry.content:
This adds a session policy to the FeaturePromoController that uses

stored data (including data provided by the session manager) to

determine if a promo should be allowed to be shown.



When V2 is not enabled, the behavior is to allow higher-priority promos

to preempt lower-priority ones. This is not a change from current

behavior, but does explicitly move the logic for these cases into the

session policy.



When V2 is enabled, additional session start grace period and multi-day

cooldowns are applied to heavyweight, low-priority ("nudge") promos

such as snooze, custom action, and tutorial promos.



Follow-up items will include:

- Incorporating non-IPH announcements and promotions into the cooldown

logic, so that, for example, a non-IPH legal notice would still

trigger a cooldown.

- Hooks for recording UMA data to characterize typical idle and

active behavior patterns.

- Hooks for recording UMA data to characterize when and how promos are

blocked from showing, especially around the grace period and cooldown

rules.

This adds a session manager to the FeaturePromoController that tracks

browser idle state and determines when a new "session" starts based on

constants tied to the new V2 flag.

are fully tested. UserEducationServiceFactory has been modified to

create default versions of all of the necessary helper classes, which

can be overridden in tests.

cooldowns between low-priority IPH.

- Logic for gating IPH when v2 is enabled.

- Hooks for recording UMA data to characterize typical idle and

active behavior patterns.

tests that expect nobody to be watching idle state, and to test classes

that do not create an idle service.

entry.title: serial: Fix DCHECK crash when disconnection happens during abort
entry.content:
The original implementation of

`SerialPortUnderlyingSink::OnFlushOrDrain` assumed that a valid

`pending_operation_` would always be available. However, this assumption

was flawed as disconnection could occur before the completion of the

abort operation.



To address this issue, the serialPort-disconnect-during-abort test was

introduced to trigger the crash and demonstrate that the disconnection

handler cleared pending_operation_. The revised code now checks the validity of `pending_operation_` before attempting to resolve it.



This modification ensures that

`SerialPortUnderlyingSink::OnFlushOrDrain` correctly even when

disconnection occurs during an abort operation, preventing potential

crashes.

entry.title: Ship No-Vary-Search header and hint
entry.content:
The way these two features interact is:

- No-Vary-Search response header allows the prefetch cache to use

inexact matching if the prefetch already has received head at time

of navigation.

- No-Vary-Search hint allows the navigation to wait for the head

of the in progress prefetch that has inexact match with navigation

URL based on its No-Vary-Search hint.



In order to ship we use an approach similar to

go/graduating-from-finch#optional-leave-a-finch-hook to allow

unshipping and return to Origin Trial by using Finch config

without requiring a binary re-spin of Chrome.



The following are added:

- a feature param enabled by default

(kPrefetchNoVarySearchShippedByDefault) attached to the feature

PrefetchNoVarySearch which marks No-Vary-Search response header

as shipped by default. Disabling this feature param via Finch

unships No-Vary-Search header.

- a base feature for runtime enabled feature

SpeculationRulesNoVarySearchHint disabled by default. This allows

us to turn off No-Vary-Search hint functionality in the origin

trial independently of No-Vary-Search response header

functionality

- a runtime enabled feature

SpeculationRulesNoVarySearchHintShippedByDefault enabled by

default which marks Speculation Rules No-Vary-Search hint as

shipped by default. Disabling this runtime enabled feature

via Finch unships Speculation Rules No-Vary-Search hint.



The kill-switch functionality will work in the following ways:

- to unship No-Vary-Search response header while allowing

Origin Trial to continue: disable

kPrefetchNoVarySearchShippedByDefault via Finch.

- to unship Speculation Rules No-Vary-Search hint functionality

while allowing Origin Trial to continue: disable

SpeculationRulesNoVarySearchHintShippedByDefault via Finch.

- to stop Speculation Rules No-Vary-Search hint functionality

in the origin trial: disable both

SpeculationRulesNoVarySearchHintShippedByDefault and

SpeculationRulesNoVarySearchHint via Finch.

- to unship both functionality for all including Origin Trial

users: disable SpeculationRulesNoVarySearchHintShippedByDefault,

SpeculationRulesNoVarySearchHint, PrefetchNoVarySearch via Finch.



Links to Intents to Ship:

- NVS hint: https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/blink-dev/c/TZSsl2iCuA4/m/5BVuLhoBCAAJ

- NVS header: https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/blink-dev/c/XnG5BF3uoeE/m/th2iMQcBCAAJ

active user switch. Causing full restore to still show notification when

fws is handling the actual workspace sync.



This change is to disable this code path as well.
